I've spent the better part of a day taking a look at _why_ getByRole is much slower.  In our case, the slowdown is actually coming from `dom-accessibility-api`, currently used here:

https://github.com/testing-library/dom-testing-library/blob/84bf52f1b2b30f34e3a709e5bdd32e14623d6f60/src/queries/role.js#L150

If the textContent is pulled out of the node instead of using dom-accessibility-api to compute the accessible name, performance increases drastically.

Test time while using `computeAccessibleName`
> should show all keys in the layout (3665 ms)

Test time while comparing `element.textContent`
> should show all keys in the layout (300 ms)

In my test, that speeds my test up by 12 times!

Why?  I'm not too sure, but it may have something to do with jsdom's implementation of `getComputedStyle`, which historically has had poor performance.  [dom-accessibility-api](https://github.com/eps1lon/dom-accessibility-api)'s [computeAccessibleName](https://github.com/eps1lon/dom-accessibility-api/blob/2cf0211b8cd6ea2e7d6db0a677fde245fe0b2563/sources/accessible-name.ts#L32) function eventually calls `window.getComputedStyle`.  I found [an old bug](https://github.com/jsdom/jsdom/issues/1560) with jsdom which mentioned that they had poor performance and the ticket was closed after a bit of finger-pointing.  This was 5 years ago though, so it may not be relevant.

---

@kentcdodds - Would you support adding another option to the `*ByRole` selector which allows a user to specify that they are looking for text directly?  This would allow the selector to bypass `dom-accessibility-api` for instances where a user knows the name that they are looking for.  I'm happy to implement.

While a catch-all selector is nice to have, there are some serious performance gains to be had here while still maintaining confidence.

```ts
// Proposed use
getByRole('button', { text: 'Exact text match' });

// Proposed pseudo-code change
// https://github.com/testing-library/dom-testing-library/blob/84bf52f1b2b30f34e3a709e5bdd32e14623d6f60/src/queries/role.js#L150
    .filter(element => {
      if(options.text !== undefined) {
          return element.textContent === options.text
      }

      if (name === undefined) {
        // Don't care
        return true
      }

      return matches(
        computeAccessibleName(element, {
          computedStyleSupportsPseudoElements:
            getConfig().computedStyleSupportsPseudoElements,
        }),
        element,
        name,
        text => text,
      )
    })
```

I've noticed that `waitFor` bypasses the set interval when mutations happen, for example with this
```js
test.only('test', async () => {
  render(<ComplexComponent />);

  let now = performance.now();

  await waitFor(
    () => {
      console.log(`check: ${performance.now() - now}ms`);
      now = performance.now();
      expect(1).toBe(2);
    },
    {
      interval: 2000,
      timeout: 6100
      // mutationObserverOptions: { subtree: false, attributes: true }
    }
  );

  console.log(`check: ${performance.now() - now}ms`);
});
```
I see this logged:
```
check: 1.0617000000002008ms
check: 54.92289999999957ms
check: 87.00720000000001ms
check: 24.19459999999981ms
check: 28.44000000000051ms
check: 37.776199999999335ms
check: 24.651099999999133ms
check: 1740.7797999999993ms
check: 1999.6796000000013ms
check: 1999.6800999999996ms
```

If I tweak the options with `mutationObserverOptions: { subtree: false, attributes: true }` then I get something more reasonable:
```
check: 1.095499999999447ms
check: 1999.2367999999997ms
check: 2001.2246999999998ms
check: 2000.5632999999998ms
```

So I think `waitFor`/`findBy` should respect the (default) interval, and throttle even when dom mutations happen. Otherwise it doesn't give enough room for async operations to run to completion. Especially when each `waitFor` run is longer than the set interval.

Another benchmark:
```js
console.time('check');
let cancelButton = await screen.findByRole('button', { name: 'Cancel' });
console.timeEnd('check');
```
Result: `check: 2.586s`

```js
console.time('check');
let cancelButton;
await waitFor(async () => {
  await new Promise((resolve) => {
    setTimeout(resolve, 100);
  });
  cancelButton = screen.queryByRole('button', { name: 'Cancel' });
  expect(cancelButton).toBeInTheDocument();
});
console.timeEnd('check');
```
Result: `check: 1.096s`

So yeah, delaying things is ~2x faster 🤔

If `waitFor` had to respect the interval, then we wouldn't have a need for the mutation observer, which could make simpler cases worse, so maybe we shouldn't do that.

What if, instead, the mutation observer would schedule the `waitFor` run with `requestIdleCallback`?

```js
let idleCallbackId = null;

const mo = new MutationObserver(() => {
  if (idleCallbackId === null) return;
  idleCallbackId = requestIdleCallback(waitForCallback);
});

function nextInterval() {
  cancelIdleCallback(idleCallbackId);
  idleCallbackId = null;
  waitForCallback();
}
```

If there is always code running then it might never be truly "idle", but the interval checks will take care of that anyway.
This might actually work perfectly. Just needs some testing.

https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Window/requestIdleCallback
https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Window/cancelIdleCallback
It was also added to the TS types in the 4.4 release:
https://github.com/microsoft/TypeScript-DOM-lib-generator/issues/1029#issuecomment-869224737

I would also swap `setInterval` with a `setTimeout`, so there's an even interval between runs, otherwise we might end up with multiple runs back to back as they can take longer than the interval.

